Day 01 — Linux Fundamentals & Basic Commands

Beginner-friendly Linux notes designed for DevOps learning and GitHub showcase.

Introduction to Linux
What is Linux?

Linux is an open-source operating system based on Unix architecture.
It is widely used in:

Servers
Cloud Computing
DevOps
Cybersecurity
Containers and Kubernetes

Most production servers run on Linux because it is:

Stable
Secure
Fast
Lightweight
Highly customizable
Linux Terminal
What is a Terminal?

A terminal is a command-line interface (CLI) that allows users to interact with the Linux operating system using commands.

DevOps engineers primarily work with Linux through the terminal.

Linux File System Basics

Linux follows a hierarchical directory structure.

Example:

/
├── home
├── etc
├── var
├── bin
├── usr
└── tmp
Important Directories
Directory	Purpose
/home	User files and folders
/etc	Configuration files
/var	Logs and variable data
/bin	Essential system commands
/tmp	Temporary files
Basic Linux Commands
1. pwd
Definition

pwd stands for Present Working Directory.

It displays the current directory path.

Syntax
pwd
Example
$ pwd
/home/ubuntu
Use Case
Used to identify your current location inside the Linux file system.

2. ls
Definition

ls lists files and directories.

Syntax
ls
Example
$ ls
Documents Downloads notes.txt
Common Options
Command	Description
ls -l	Long listing format
ls -a	Show hidden files
ls -lh	Human-readable file sizes
Example
ls -l

Output:

drwxr-xr-x 2 ubuntu ubuntu 4096 May 21 projects
3. cd
Definition

cd stands for Change Directory.

Used to navigate between directories.

Syntax
cd directory_name
Examples
Move into a directory
cd Downloads
Move back one directory
cd ..
Go to home directory
cd ~
4. mkdir
Definition

mkdir stands for Make Directory.

Used to create new directories.

Syntax
mkdir directory_name
Example
mkdir linux-notes
Verify
ls

Output:

linux-notes
5. touch
Definition

touch creates empty files.

Syntax
touch filename
Example
touch notes.txt
Verify
ls

Output:

notes.txt
6. clear
Definition

Clears the terminal screen.

Syntax
clear
7. whoami
Definition

Displays the currently logged-in user.

Syntax
whoami
Example
$ whoami
ubuntu
